    {
      "id": "432d7b0fd50ac470dff05294ec69d3d51561d9b3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2015-01-05 18:13:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\nTypically, including asm/ headers is the wrong thing to do. It may also be that the use of NR_CPUS is the wrong thing also, and the code should be using num_available_cpus() or num_possible_cpus() is better for a number of reasons (less memory usage, more portable, etc.)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e9fa68be46569670218228a6b1f0955b007583d6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2015-01-05 18:49:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nCC [M]  /work/lustre/head3/lnet/klnds/socklnd/socklnd.o\nIn file included from /work/lustre/linux-2.6.32-431.el6/arch/x86/include/asm/irq.h:11:0,\n                 from /work/lustre/head3/lnet/klnds/socklnd/socklnd.h:34,\n                 from /work/lustre/head3/lnet/klnds/socklnd/socklnd.c:44:\n/work/lustre/linux-2.6.32-431.el6/arch/x86/include/asm/irq_vectors.h:171:7: error: \"NR_CPUS\" is not defined [-Werror=undef]\nIn file included from /work/lustre/head3/lnet/klnds/socklnd/socklnd.h:34:0,\n                 from /work/lustre/head3/lnet/klnds/socklnd/socklnd.c:44:\n/work/lustre/linux-2.6.32-431.el6/arch/x86/include/asm/irq.h:38:1: error: unknown type name 'bool'\n/work/lustre/linux-2.6.32-431.el6/arch/x86/include/asm/irq.h:38:45: error: 'struct pt_regs' declared inside parameter list [-Werror]\n/work/lustre/linux-2.6.32-431.el6/arch/x86/include/asm/irq.h:38:45: error: its scope is only this definition or declaration, which is probably not what you want [-Werror]\n/work/lustre/linux-2.6.32-431.el6/arch/x86/include/asm/irq.h:40:35: error: 'struct pt_regs' declared inside parameter list [-Werror]\n/work/lustre/linux-2.6.32-431.el6/arch/x86/include/asm/irq.h:43:37: error: expected ')' before numeric constant\ncc1: all warnings being treated as errors",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d30133c344d27e533d1aaab876812d1f76f9030b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2015-01-05 18:49:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nNR_CPUS isn't used directly by Lustre, so this is a workaround for the kernel's issue.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "9f36b3d11b678756c1e6a7ebabb6db745d89153d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2015-01-05 19:20:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nNR_CPUS is defined in threads.h which is included in many linux headers. Could you try moving <asm/irq.h> to after <linux/unistd.h>. If that doesn't work try placing it after <libcfs/libcfs.h>. The cpu partition header should be included in libcfs.h.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "93399a135f94460a09431b44bce08291451adffd",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2015-01-05 19:31:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nit needs to be defined before including linux/arch/x86/include/asm/irq.h",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "160d83f87ddc02ae4c4f301906799e2784e87d3a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2015-01-05 19:56:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAlex are you comfortable with removing '#include <asm/irq.h>' and replacing with '#include <linux/interrupt.h>'? It looks to me like that is what was intended anyway. The only relevant thing I see in socklnd/ is in_irq() and that is *not* provided by asm/irq.h.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
